{"id": "14927", "revid": "45996740", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=14927", "title": "Gargantuan", "text": "Gargantuan\u00a0is a Voodoo\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Witch%20Doctor\"&gt;Witch Doctor&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0skill, loosely based on the &lt;a href=\"Golem\"&gt;Golem&lt;/a&gt; skill type.\nIn-game.\nSummons a single colossal zombie that fights at the Witch Doctor's side until it dies. It attacks for of the Witch Doctor's damage, and has roughly of the Witch Doctor's &lt;a href=\"Life\"&gt;Life&lt;/a&gt;, sharing most of the master's stats. Any destructible objects in its wake are destroyed.\nOnly one such zombie can be summoned at a time. The zombie is summoned at the cursor's location, anywhere within 80 yards."}
{"id": "3347", "revid": "47915220", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=3347", "title": "Gargantuan Beast", "text": "The Gargantuan Beast is a &lt;a href=\"Wendigo\"&gt;Wendigo&lt;/a&gt; variant in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\".\nLore.\nGargantuan Beasts are the weakest of all Wendigo sub-species. Extremely territorial, these creatures attack anything they see as a threat to their power...which is pretty much anything they encounter.\nIn-game.\nGargantuan Beasts are the first type of Wendigo that can be encountered in the first act of Diablo II, in the: \nWhile not as common as most other foes, they are easily-noticed by their giant size and occasional grunting."}
{"id": "28096", "revid": "1773829", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=28096", "title": "Garganug", "text": "Garganug, King of the Golgors is a &lt;a href=\"Unique%20Monsters\"&gt;unique&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Colossal%20Golgor\"&gt;Colossal Golgor&lt;/a&gt; that can be found in &lt;a href=\"Rakkis%20Crossing\"&gt;Rakkis Crossing&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Act%20III%20%28Diablo%20III%29\"&gt;Act III&lt;/a&gt; of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". He is usually located at the \"very\" end of the Crossing, just before the &lt;a href=\"Edge%20of%20the%20Abyss\"&gt;Edge of the Abyss&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "9530", "revid": "47915220", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=9530", "title": "Gargoyle", "text": "Gargoyles (a.k.a. Signum Vitiosum) are a type of flying &lt;a href=\"demon\"&gt;demon&lt;/a&gt;.\nLore.\nGargoyles are carved figures, representing grotesque &lt;a href=\"human\"&gt;human&lt;/a&gt;s and animals, corrupted and animated by evil. They are capable of flight. With no need for food or water, Gargoyles can stand motionless for years. However, should a mortal draw near, they are quick to break their immobility and attack.\nThe act of transforming from flesh to stone allows a Gargoyle to heal any wounds that it has suffered. Adventurers should either avoid these demons or hunt them down until they are dead. Allowing them to flee will enable Gargoyles to return in full force.\nGargoyles are fairly intelligent and evil, and so sometimes serve a more powerful master.\nHistory.\nIn ages past, it was customary to decorate buildings with stone statues of demons that were enchanted to serve as guardians and protectors of those within. The misshapen figures of the statues were designed to taunt and anger any demons that attempted to gain entrance. &lt;a href=\"Diablo\"&gt;Diablo&lt;/a&gt; worked to unlock the wards that protected these granite images, and eventually was able to gild them with a Hadean life. The Gargoyles arose from their captive sleep and swooped down to prey upon those whom they were created to protect. Naturally, the remaining statues were immediately destroyed, but there are Signum that escaped and continue to terrorise the innocent to this day. They have spread to many dark and deep parts of the &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;world&lt;/a&gt;.\nIn-game.\nDiablo I.\nGargoyles are encountered in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20I\"&gt;Diablo I&lt;/a&gt;\". They can usually be found on the lower levels of the catacombs, as well as the first level of the caves. These vile creatures have many magical immunities, making them tough opponents for magic wielding adventurers.\nDiablo Immortal.\nGargoyles reappear in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\" in the &lt;a href=\"Mad%20King%27s%20Breach\"&gt;Mad King's Breach&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"dungeon%20%28Diablo%20Immortal%29\"&gt;dungeon&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href=\"Zakarum%20Graveyard\"&gt;Zakarum Graveyard&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "6728", "revid": "1687225", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6728", "title": "Gargoyle's Bite", "text": "Gargoyle's Bite is a &lt;a href=\"Unique%20Items\"&gt;unique&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Winged%20Harpoon\"&gt;Winged Harpoon&lt;/a&gt; from \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\".\nWhereas &lt;a href=\"Demon%27s%20Arch\"&gt;Demon's Arch&lt;/a&gt; deals &lt;a href=\"Fire\"&gt;Fire&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Lightning%20Damage\"&gt;Lightning Damage&lt;/a&gt;, Gargoyle's Bite focuses on &lt;a href=\"Poison%20Damage\"&gt;Poison Damage&lt;/a&gt;. Although it is certainly safer to poison an enemy from afar, poison damage is only effective over time, making it a slower-acting attack than most. Still, Gargoyle's Bite is a practical weapon nonetheless, and its &lt;a href=\"life\"&gt;life&lt;/a&gt; leech is particularly useful.\nStats.\nThrow Damage: (30-36) To (215-254)\nOne-Hand Damage: (75-89) To (98-115)\nRequired Level: 70\nRequired Strength: 76\nRequired Dexterity: 145\nJavelin Class \u2013 Fast Attack Speed\nMax Stack (80)"}
{"id": "5613", "revid": "3423357", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5613", "title": "Gargoyle Head", "text": "Gargoyle Heads are totemic &lt;a href=\"Shields\"&gt;shields&lt;/a&gt; used exclusively by &lt;a href=\"Necromancers\"&gt;Necromancers&lt;/a&gt;.\nShrunken Heads will also receive an &lt;a href=\"Auto%20Mod%23Necromancer%20Shrunken%20Heads\"&gt;Auto Mod&lt;/a&gt; that will add &lt;a href=\"Poison\"&gt;Poison&lt;/a&gt; damage to every attack."}
{"id": "3434", "revid": "47915220", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=3434", "title": "Gargoyle Trap", "text": "Gargoyle Traps at first seem to be just statues. However, when one wanders close to it, it spits out &lt;a href=\"Fireball\"&gt;Fireball&lt;/a&gt;s in every direction. These sentries are incredibly strong and durable and many warriors must destroy it with strong melee weapons. A suitable &lt;a href=\"Resistances\"&gt;fire resistance&lt;/a&gt; should prevent heavy damage inflicted by these traps. These statues are found in &lt;a href=\"Jail\"&gt;Jail 1-3&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Catacombs\"&gt;Catacombs 1-3&lt;/a&gt;.\nAs Gargoyle Traps are non-living entities, &lt;a href=\"Life\"&gt;Life&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Mana\"&gt;Mana&lt;/a&gt; cannot be stolen from them.\nGargoyle Traps are immune to &lt;a href=\"Cold\"&gt;Cold&lt;/a&gt; on both Nightmare and Hell difficulties.\nBackground.\nLeft behind by paranoid mages to safeguard their treasure troves from prying fingers, these enchanted sentries animate and emit fireballs at those who approach too closely. An interesting quirk of these guardians is that they are not activated by the proximity of the many monsters that roam the areas where they are found. This has led many sages to speculate that they may have been created even before mankind knew of the existence of Demons.\nStatistics.\nDevelopment.\nIn version 1.00 Gargoyle Trap spat two Fireballs instead of one."}
{"id": "40592", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=40592", "title": "Garma", "text": "Garma is a .\nIn &lt;a href=\"Timeline%231255\"&gt;1255&lt;/a&gt;, he and a group of his fellow Barbarians kidnapped &lt;a href=\"Marta\"&gt;Marta&lt;/a&gt;. However, they returned her to &lt;a href=\"Bastion%27s%20Keep\"&gt;Bastion's Keep&lt;/a&gt; a mere two hours later, after she was able to reason with him. Over the next &lt;a href=\"Timeline%231285\"&gt;thirty years&lt;/a&gt;, he would send her hides by way of apology."}
