{"id": "32140", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=32140", "title": "Matt Uelmen", "text": "Matt Uelmen is a composer who worked with &lt;a href=\"Blizzard%20Entertainment\"&gt;Blizzard Entertainment&lt;/a&gt;. \nBiography.\nIn his childhood, Uelmen played classical piano, before moving on to other instruments and genres. In 1993, he sent demos of his work \"to every developer who was working on 16-bit games in the San Francisco Bay Area.\" He created the music using the technical specs of the Sega Genesis.\nHis works include the &lt;a href=\"Tristram\"&gt;Tristram&lt;/a&gt; theme from the original \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20%28Game%29\"&gt;Diablo&lt;/a&gt;\", and worked on the music for \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\" and its . He also worked on the original \"&lt;a href=\"StarCraft\"&gt;StarCraft&lt;/a&gt;\" and worked on the music of &lt;a href=\"Blizzard%20North\"&gt;Blizzard North&lt;/a&gt;'s &lt;a href=\"Diablo%202.5\"&gt;version&lt;/a&gt; of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\" as well. &lt;a href=\"Russel%20Brower\"&gt;Russel Brower&lt;/a&gt; has commented that Uelmen's style in this time was more \"Wagnerian\" (a comparison to Richard Wagner); the music being \"big and powerful,\" whereas previously, Uelmen's scores had been more eclectic, using a lot of found sound. Reportedly, Uelmen's music style influenced the direction of the game's early development.\nIn the early 2000s, Uelmen was aware of the tensions gripping Blizzard North as the team collapsed into dysfunction. For his part, Uelmen wanted to keep the team together, and was caught offguard when &lt;a href=\"David%20Brevik\"&gt;David Brevik&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Max%20Schaefer\"&gt;Max Schaefer&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Erich%20Schaefer\"&gt;Erich Schaefer&lt;/a&gt; resigned. While some Blizzard North members left with their founders, Uelmen wasn't among them; he was raising a family, paying for his wife's law school course, and didn't feel financially secure enough to risk jumping ship. Thus, at least initially, he remained at Blizzard North. However, the company was shut down in 2005, and it took awhile for Uelmen to learn what had happened; his wife had gone into labor, and he was in the hospital when he learnt of Blizzard North's closure. When he finally got to see &lt;a href=\"Mike%20Morhaime\"&gt;Mike Morhaime&lt;/a&gt;, he took Morhaime's offer to work at Blizard Irvine. When he arrived, his first assignment was to write music for \"&lt;a href=\"World%20of%20Warcraft\"&gt;World of Warcraft&lt;/a&gt;\".\nUelmen performed a track for \"World of Warcraft: The Burning Crusade\". He left Blizzard in 2007, and joined &lt;a href=\"https%3A//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Runic_Games\"&gt;Runic Games&lt;/a&gt; in 2009, where he provided the composition for \"&lt;a href=\"https%3A//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Torchlight\"&gt;Torchlight&lt;/a&gt;\"."}
{"id": "30053", "revid": "3423357", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=30053", "title": "Matthew Berger", "text": "Matthew Berger is a senior game designer for \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\".\nBiography.\nBerger joined &lt;a href=\"Blizzard%20Entertainment\"&gt;Blizzard Entertainment&lt;/a&gt; in 2012 as a senior level designer after holding numerous design lead roles at Relic Entertainment, including multiplayer lead on \"Company of Heroes 2\", campaign lead on \"Warhammer 40,000: Space Marine\", lead designer on \"Company of Heroes Online\", and campaign supervisor on \"Warhammer 40,000: Dawn of War II\". He is also credited on several other titles as a designer, including multiple \"Dawn of War\" and \"Company of Heroes\" expansions.\nBerger was part of the core design group that was charged with bringing Diablo III from PC to console. While his expertise has been applied to numerous areas of the game, his core focus was on updating boss fight mechanics and on gameplay elements like &lt;a href=\"Monk\"&gt;Monk&lt;/a&gt; combo skills and console-specific features as well as developing &lt;a href=\"Rift%20Guardian\"&gt;Rift Bosses&lt;/a&gt; for PC.\nBy 2017, Berger was the game's senior game designer. By 2018, he was the senior designer for \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\"."}
