{"id": "6470", "revid": "4889310", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6470", "title": "Medusa's Gaze", "text": "Medusa's Gaze is a &lt;a href=\"Unique%20Items\"&gt;unique&lt;/a&gt; , a type of &lt;a href=\"Shields\"&gt;shield&lt;/a&gt; from \"\".\nProbably the most interesting feature of this shield is that it has a &lt;a href=\"Lower%20Resist\"&gt;Lower Resist&lt;/a&gt; proc. This can reduce the below-immunity &lt;a href=\"resistances\"&gt;resistances&lt;/a&gt; of monsters nearby by 51%, and break immunities below 110 resistance. This can greatly aid elemental attackers with or without &lt;a href=\"Conviction\"&gt;Conviction&lt;/a&gt; available already, although the extremely high &lt;a href=\"strength\"&gt;strength&lt;/a&gt; requirement and the fact that the proc is activated when struck means that casters should consider their options carefully before trying to make use of this. There are some melee builds that rely on elemental damage, however, which are much more fit to take advantage of this. Melee attackers can also make good use of the &lt;a href=\"Slow\"&gt;Slow&lt;/a&gt;s Target by 20% mod as well as the life leech bonus.\nMedusa's Gaze also has the interesting ability to cast a very high level upon death. This property is similar to the properties of the unique &lt;a href=\"jewels\"&gt;jewels&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Rainbow%20Facets\"&gt;Rainbow Facets&lt;/a&gt;. Perhaps to infuriate others in player versus player, one could equip Medusa's Gaze and other &lt;a href=\"Socketed%20Items\"&gt;Socketed Items&lt;/a&gt; with \"Upon Death\" Rainbow Facets inserted, causing quite a boom upon death. \nRather arbitrarily, Medusa's Gaze has the potential to give a very large boost to Cold Resist. Although certainly useful against Cold Enchanted enemies in &lt;a href=\"difficulty\"&gt;difficulty&lt;/a&gt;, it does leave the rest of a player's resistances exposed.\nStats.\nDefense: 405-453 \nRequired Level: 76\nRequired Strength: 219\nDurability: 92\nChance to Block:\nPaladin &lt;a href=\"Smite\"&gt;Smite&lt;/a&gt; Damage: 18 To 28"}
{"id": "11728", "revid": "865253", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11728", "title": "Mefis", "text": ""}
{"id": "31388", "revid": "47915220", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=31388", "title": "Megademon", "text": "Megademons (a.k.a. Balrogs) are a type of &lt;a href=\"demon\"&gt;demon&lt;/a&gt;.\nLore.\nThe Megademons are one of &lt;a href=\"Burning%20Hells\"&gt;Hell&lt;/a&gt;'s most potent weapons. These archetypical demons are spawned from the hottest fires of Hell, with no other purpose than to act as a scourge to &lt;a href=\"human\"&gt;mortal&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"soul\"&gt;soul&lt;/a&gt;s. They are often found in conjunction with important &lt;a href=\"tomes\"&gt;tomes&lt;/a&gt; of evil, wicked artifacts, or guarding vital thoroughfares. At 12 feet tall, these creatures tower over their lesser kin, their leathery wings and treacherous horns making them an awesome sight to behold. Megademons are formidable opponents, and attack without hesitation. Wielding jagged blades, they seek to hew the limbs from their victims and bring a bloody end to any who would oppose the might of their dark lords. Even disarmed, they are capable of inflicting serious damage with their razor-sharp claws and wings. But their most fearsome weapon is their hellish breath, with which they cook their opponents alive.\nTypes.\nVarious types of Megademons exist, and have been referred to as an extended \"Balrog clan.\" Ranks include:\nOther types of megademons include the &lt;a href=\"Pit%20Lord\"&gt;Pit Lord&lt;/a&gt;s and &lt;a href=\"Venom%20Lord\"&gt;Venom Lord&lt;/a&gt;s.\nIn-game.\nDiablo I.\nMegademons are found in the Caves and Hell levels of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20I\"&gt;Diablo I&lt;/a&gt;\". In this game, \"Balrog\" is the de facto name for the monster class, as well as a specific variant.\nDiablo II.\nMegademons return in of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\".\nDiablo III.\nIn \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\", Megademons do not reappear. Their role and abilities are represented by &lt;a href=\"Oppressor\"&gt;Oppressor&lt;/a&gt;s and &lt;a href=\"Warscarred%20Ravager\"&gt;Warscarred Ravager&lt;/a&gt;s in and ."}
{"id": "44874", "revid": "47915220", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=44874", "title": "Megademon4", "text": ""}
{"id": "3167", "revid": "47915220", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=3167", "title": "Megademon (Diablo II)", "text": "Megademons are a class of &lt;a href=\"monster\"&gt;monster&lt;/a&gt; encountered in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\".\nIn-game.\nThe Megademons are essentially an updated version of the &lt;a href=\"Balrog%20%28Diablo%20I%29\"&gt;Balrog&lt;/a&gt; encountered in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20I\"&gt;Diablo I&lt;/a&gt;\", possessing the same body structure and ability to cast their own version of the &lt;a href=\"Inferno%20%28monster%20skill%29\"&gt;Inferno&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Fire_Spells\"&gt;Spell&lt;/a&gt;.\nAll types of Megademons have the ability to cast an &lt;a href=\"Inferno%20%28Diablo%20II%29\"&gt;Inferno&lt;/a&gt; spell to incinerate their opponents. &lt;a href=\"Fire\"&gt;Fire&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Resistances\"&gt;Resistance&lt;/a&gt; and fire &lt;a href=\"Absorption\"&gt;absorb&lt;/a&gt; are a good way to stay safe when challenging them, while distance and a strong attack are the best solution to ensure their &lt;a href=\"death\"&gt;death&lt;/a&gt;.\nWhile there are four different types of Megademons encountered in the first game, there are only three types encountered in the second game."}
{"id": "40407", "revid": "47915220", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=40407", "title": "Megademon (Guest)", "text": "This is a page for &lt;a href=\"Nightmare%20%28difficulty%29\"&gt;Nightmare&lt;/a&gt;/&lt;a href=\"Hell%20%28difficulty%29\"&gt;Hell&lt;/a&gt; difficulty exclusive &lt;a href=\"Guest%20Monsters\"&gt;Guest&lt;/a&gt; variations of &lt;a href=\"Megademon%20%28Diablo%20II%29\"&gt;Megademon&lt;/a&gt;. \nAll Guest Megademons have a 15/25% chance to deal &lt;a href=\"Cold\"&gt;Fire&lt;/a&gt; damage with melee attacks on &lt;a href=\"Nightmare%20%28difficulty%29\"&gt;Nightmare&lt;/a&gt;/&lt;a href=\"Hell%20%28difficulty%29\"&gt;Hell&lt;/a&gt;. Pandemonium Pit Lords are one of the most powerful monsters in the game, with their immunities to everything. "}
{"id": "51632", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51632", "title": "Mehrwen", "text": "Mehrwen along with &lt;a href=\"Ksathra\"&gt;Ksathra&lt;/a&gt;, was the last sister priest-empresses of &lt;a href=\"Pelghain\"&gt;Pelghain&lt;/a&gt;.\nBiography.\nMehrwen was fond of introspection. She believed that knowledge could be found in understanding the essence of your &lt;a href=\"soul\"&gt;soul&lt;/a&gt; as it has always been, and wisdom in accepting what it will become. She also taught her people about purification of the soul; that it should occur first alone, over days. Then, purification should occur \"in the sight of others,\" over the course of a life's ordeals.\nAs the power of the empresses winnowed, they argued over the direction to take their people. Ksathra suggested uplifting a few so that they could shepherd their fellows, which Mehrwen said that it would be better to provide a small amount of power to all, that none may claim dominion. It is widely believed that Ksathra struck the first blow in anger. The result was a civil war that destroyed the empire, and left the &lt;a href=\"Cold%20Isles\"&gt;Cold Isles&lt;/a&gt; beset by storm and sea.\nIt is believed that while mortally injured, Mehrwen swam away from Ksathra to &lt;a href=\"the%20Spiral\"&gt;the Spiral&lt;/a&gt;, where people could find and praise her in &lt;a href=\"death\"&gt;death&lt;/a&gt;. Her dying breath supposedly formed the mists that shroud the region. The purest and bravest &lt;a href=\"Tempest\"&gt;Tempest&lt;/a&gt;s are sent on dangerous voices to breathe in the mists, hear the whispering voices of an earlier age, and grow in knowledge and power to command sea and sky as empresses such as Mehrwen did. \nPresently, Mehrwen is worshipped by the people of the Cold Isles, in tall spires with roofs open to the air, as if inviting all to join in her rule. However, the legend of &lt;a href=\"Xekorendaag\"&gt;Xekorendaag&lt;/a&gt; states that the empresses' fury cursed the Isles so long as their descendants remained on Pelghain. When the people began to brave the deluges and hurricanes, arrogantly building tall cities and monuments, a great serpent drove into their settlements, consuming families and carving the isles apart as it did. Reproached, the people moved their settlements away from the capital, and the serpent faded to memory."}
