{"id": "7020", "revid": "1773829", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=7020", "title": "Messerschmidt's Reaver", "text": "Messerschmidt's Reaver is a unique axe in the Diablo series:"}
{"id": "7105", "revid": "1773829", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=7105", "title": "Messerschmidt's Reaver (Diablo I)", "text": "Messerschmidt's Reaver is a &lt;a href=\"Unique%20Items\"&gt;Unique&lt;/a&gt; Great Axe found in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20I\"&gt;Diablo I&lt;/a&gt;\", possessing a high amount of damage and a meager boost to all attributes. Its large Hit Point penalty and lack of To-Hit bonus make it inadequate for use in Nightmare and Hell difficulties.\nIt returned in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\".\nIt is also found in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\" as a legendary weapon, with its description speculating it was the weapon of choice for &lt;a href=\"Aidan\"&gt;Aidan&lt;/a&gt; during the events of \"Diablo I\", referring to its high popularity in the original game."}
{"id": "6776", "revid": "1773829", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6776", "title": "Messerschmidt's Reaver (Diablo II)", "text": "Messerschmidt's Reaver is an &lt;a href=\"Elite%20Items\"&gt;elite&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Unique%20Items\"&gt;unique&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Champion%20Axe\"&gt;Champion Axe&lt;/a&gt; from \"\".\nRather similar to fellow unique &lt;a href=\"Axes\"&gt;axe&lt;/a&gt; , Messerschmidt's Reaver gives a very large bonus to Maximum damage that grows with higher levels. However, Messerschmidt's Reaver can be seen as a \"safer\" weapon for several reasons: it has a higher minimum damage, is less dependent on added &lt;a href=\"Fire\"&gt;Fire&lt;/a&gt; damage, and it is also slightly faster, allowing for more hits when compared to the Hellslayer.\nStats.\nTwo-Hand Damage: \nRequired Level: 70\nRequired Strength: 167\nRequired Dexterity: 59\nDurability: 75\nAxe Class \u2013 Fast Attack Speed"}
{"id": "21302", "revid": "1773829", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=21302", "title": "Messerschmidt's Reaver (Diablo III)", "text": "Messerschmidt's Reaver is a &lt;a href=\"Legendary%20Items\"&gt;legendary&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Two-Handed%20Axes\"&gt;two-handed axe&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". It requires character level 50 to drop.\nAside from being famous for its appearances in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20I\"&gt;Diablo I&lt;/a&gt;\" and \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\" (the description implies it could be the weapon &lt;a href=\"Aidan\"&gt;Aidan&lt;/a&gt; himself once wielded), this axe also has considerable damage bonuses and &lt;a href=\"Life\"&gt;Life&lt;/a&gt; per Kill statistic.\nAs of patch &lt;a href=\"Patch%202.6.6%20%28Diablo%20III%29\"&gt;Patch 2.6.6&lt;/a&gt;, it also gained a unique affix: reducing the remaining &lt;a href=\"cooldown\"&gt;cooldown&lt;/a&gt; of one of your skills by 1 second when you slay an enemy. This does work on assist kills and pet kills. This power did not replace any \"slot\" for the other 6 Magic Properties of the item, so it has a total of 7."}
{"id": "49454", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49454", "title": "Meston", "text": "Meston was a monk of the &lt;a href=\"Scholars%20of%20Orbei\"&gt;Scholars of Orbei&lt;/a&gt;. In &lt;a href=\"Timeline%231281\"&gt;1281&lt;/a&gt;, Monk &lt;a href=\"Kislek\"&gt;Kislek&lt;/a&gt; accused him of drinking the Scholars' stores of wine and replacing the loss with water, given how the sacramental wine had grown weak."}
{"id": "6299", "revid": "14250", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6299", "title": "Metalgrid", "text": "Metalgrid is a &lt;a href=\"Unique%20Items\"&gt;unique&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Amulets\"&gt;amulet&lt;/a&gt; from \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\".\nWith &lt;a href=\"charges\"&gt;charges&lt;/a&gt; for a very high level &lt;a href=\"Iron%20Golem\"&gt;Iron Golem&lt;/a&gt; together with &lt;a href=\"Iron%20Maiden\"&gt;Iron Maiden&lt;/a&gt;, Metalgrid lives up to its name by cursing enemies to receive quite a bit of damage they inflict back. Defensively, Metalgrid is useful too, bestowing potentially the best increase to\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Resistances\"&gt;Resistances&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Defense\"&gt;Defense&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0out of any amulet in the game. It also offers an extremely large flat attack rating boost.\nHowever, since the level required to wear Metalgrid is very high, players are nearly guaranteed to be in\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Hell%20Difficulty\"&gt;Hell Difficulty&lt;/a&gt; by the time they can wear it. The Iron Golem summoned is very frail when pitted against the opponents found in Hell, especially considering it cannot benefit from the various skills and synergies &lt;a href=\"Necromancer\"&gt;Necromancer&lt;/a&gt;s have, so it is of limited value.\u00a0Iron Maiden is likely to not be useful either, given that all enemies in Hell have very high physical resistances and large health pools compared to their damage output.\nStats.\nRequired Level: 81"}
