{"id": "23122", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=23122", "title": "Al'maiesh", "text": "Al'maiesh, the Cord of Hope, is the chosen weapon of &lt;a href=\"Auriel\"&gt;Auriel&lt;/a&gt;. The cord is said to be a manifestation of her positive qualities. Pulsing with glowing runes from end to end, the long, serpentine ribbon can heal and energize those it touches. Auriel often draped the cord around &lt;a href=\"Tyrael\"&gt;Tyrael&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Imperius\"&gt;Imperius&lt;/a&gt; during their many heated arguments, granting them clarity of thought and emotion.\nIn battle, the cord can be used as a whip, burning Auriel's enemies with rightous fire. It can also be used to bind enemies, and leave chains in its place after being retracted.\u00a0"}
{"id": "36192", "revid": "24916843", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=36192", "title": "Alabaster Fury", "text": "Alabaster Furies are &lt;a href=\"Unique%20Monsters\"&gt;Unique&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Whitefur%20Howler\"&gt;Whitefur Howler&lt;/a&gt;s found in the &lt;a href=\"Grace%20of%20Inarius\"&gt;Grace of Inarius&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Set%20Dungeon\"&gt;Set Dungeon&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\".\nIn combat, they have the Mortar and Missile Dampening affixes, the latter effectively forcing the player to fight them in melee. If allowed to charge, they can bash the player out of close combat, which also interferes with the primary task."}
{"id": "29251", "revid": "3423357", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=29251", "title": "Alabaster Gloves", "text": "Alabaster Gloves were &lt;a href=\"Legendary%20Items\"&gt;Legendary&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"gloves\"&gt;gloves&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\" to be added in Patch 2.1, but were replaced with &lt;a href=\"Vengeful%20Wind\"&gt;Vengeful Wind&lt;/a&gt;. They required &lt;a href=\"character%20level\"&gt;character level&lt;/a&gt; 70 to drop.\nThe unique affix increases the maximum stack count of &lt;a href=\"Sweeping%20Wind\"&gt;Sweeping Wind&lt;/a&gt;, and in early beta, increased the duration to 60 seconds instead. A possible reason for removal is that all other items added were class-specific."}
{"id": "48359", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=48359", "title": "Alabaster Monastery", "text": "Alabaster Monastery is a &lt;a href=\"Cathedral%20of%20Light\"&gt;Cathedral of Light&lt;/a&gt; structure located on &lt;a href=\"Alabaster%20Peak\"&gt;Alabaster Peak&lt;/a&gt;.\nLore.\nAlabaster's interior is ornate. It contains statues depicting &lt;a href=\"Inarius\"&gt;Inarius&lt;/a&gt; and paintings depicting key moments in the history of &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;Sanctuary&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href=\"Cathedral%20of%20Light\"&gt;Cathedral of Light&lt;/a&gt;. Brother &lt;a href=\"Orlin\"&gt;Orlin&lt;/a&gt; served as its custodian. Its interior is frigid, and is divided between the Halls of Ascension (forming the bulk of the monastery) and Father's Radiance (Inarius's quarters).\nHistory.\nInarius sequestered himself in Alabaster after he killed &lt;a href=\"Rathma\"&gt;Rathma&lt;/a&gt;. Years passed, with Inarius supposedly in meditation. Rumors spread about the monastery, and for a pilgrim to reach Inarius, they had to survive a pilgrimage across the &lt;a href=\"Fields%20of%20Judgment\"&gt;Fields of Judgment&lt;/a&gt;. Even for those who made it to Alabaster, not all of them returned.\nIn &lt;a href=\"Timeline%231336\"&gt;1336&lt;/a&gt;, entered the monastery, seeking a blessing from Inarius in order to continue their pursuit of &lt;a href=\"Lilith\"&gt;Lilith&lt;/a&gt;. The &lt;a href=\"angel\"&gt;angel&lt;/a&gt; refused their request.\nIn-game.\nAlabaster Monastery is located on Alabaster Peak. Functionally, it exists as a , though exists only for story purposes. The player cannot re-enter the monastery once they exit it."}
