{"id": "44900", "revid": "1773829", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=44900", "title": "Altar of Rites", "text": "The Altar of Rites is a feature in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\".\nLore.\nAn ominous altar located in the &lt;a href=\"Festering%20Woods\"&gt;Festering Woods&lt;/a&gt;, the Altar of Rites is carved from an archaic material bearing cryptic markings. It has an unsettling aura. Home to power thought to be extinct from &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;Sanctuary&lt;/a&gt;, the Altar of Rites will bestow these mystic forces upon worthy &lt;a href=\"nephalem\"&gt;nephalem&lt;/a&gt;...after a sacrifice is offered.\nIt is implied that the altar has a collective intelligence.\nHistory.\nThe altar dates back to Sanctuary's ancient past. It was rediscovered during/after the &lt;a href=\"End%20of%20Days\"&gt;End of Days&lt;/a&gt; amid a hunting/mining expedition from &lt;a href=\"New%20Tristram\"&gt;New Tristram&lt;/a&gt;, which was searching for ancient nephalem artifacts. They dug out the altar, but as they did so, a faint whisper infiltrated one of the miners' thoughts; not one voice, but a collective. The miner didn't know who these voices were, but was certain that they had to share their discovery. They hauled the altar back to New Tristram. A few days passed, many townsfolk came to view the altar, then left. Then, &lt;a href=\"the%20Nephalem\"&gt;the Nephalem&lt;/a&gt; marched into town and requested to see the altar.\nShaken to their core by the eldritch aroma of the monolith, the citizens enlisted the assistance of brave &lt;a href=\"nephalem\"&gt;nephalem&lt;/a&gt; willing to investigate. To unlock the powers of the altar, the nephalem had to travel all over &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;Sanctuary&lt;/a&gt;. They also had to deal with scores of &lt;a href=\"demon\"&gt;demon&lt;/a&gt;s hellbent on preventing them from acquiring the altar's full power.\nGameplay.\n&lt;a href=\"Season\"&gt;Season&lt;/a&gt;al characters can interact with the Altar of Rites in &lt;a href=\"New%20Tristram\"&gt;New Tristram&lt;/a&gt; as soon as &lt;a href=\"character%20level\"&gt;level&lt;/a&gt; 1. It contains 26 Seals connected in a progression tree. Seals are unlocked by sacrificing specific items to the Altar, and each one grants a bonus. Players have some discretion as to which order to unlock Seals, constrained by the tree. At the bottom of the tree are three &lt;a href=\"Potion\"&gt;Potion&lt;/a&gt; Powers which are unlocked by sacrificing &lt;a href=\"Primordial%20Ashes\"&gt;Primordial Ashes&lt;/a&gt;. A final sigil below everything else can be unlocked for free once the entire tree is complete.\nAll unlocked powers apply to every Seasonal character on the account with the same &lt;a href=\"Hardcore\"&gt;Hardcore&lt;/a&gt;/&lt;a href=\"Solo%20Self%20Found\"&gt;Solo Self Found&lt;/a&gt; status. It is expected that players can unlock the entire Altar with a reasonable amount of effort each Season. The powers last for the entire Season, after which the Altar starts over with no Seals unlocked when a new one begins.\nThe Altar was introduced for &lt;a href=\"Season\"&gt;Season&lt;/a&gt; 28 with extremely powerful bonuses. These bonuses were reduced coinciding with the Altar becoming a recurring Seasonal feature starting with Season 30, although they remain very strong.\nSeals.\nThis table shows the names, lore, and powers of every Seal or Potion, labeled by their position in the progression tree shown below.\nThe original bonuses from Season 28 are stated in footnotes. Generally, the quality of life bonuses remain the same, while combat bonuses were reduced.\nUnlocking Seals.\nPlayers must select any locked Seal on the Altar of Rites screen to see which materials they must sacrifice. The cost is the same regardless of which Seal is chosen, but after any unlock, the cost for the \"next\" unlock changes, following a preset sequence listed below. When a specific item is required, the player chooses the one to sacrifice from their &lt;a href=\"inventory\"&gt;inventory&lt;/a&gt;.\nUnlocking Potion powers works the same way, except they have their own simple sequence of &lt;a href=\"Primordial%20Ashes\"&gt;Primordial Ashes&lt;/a&gt; costs: 55, then 110, then 165 Ashes for the respective unlocks, regardless of order and independent of Seal unlock progress.\nThe topmost Seal A must always be unlocked first. For subsequent powers, at least one Seal preceding or adjacent to it (connected from above or horizontally) must first be unlocked. For example, to unlock Seal D or E, Seal B must first be unlocked. To unlock R, any one of L, M, or S must be unlocked.\nUnlocking the final, bottom sigil requires no sacrifice, only that all other Seals and Potions have been unlocked. Doing so grants its power as well as the &lt;a href=\"Wings%20of%20Terror\"&gt;Wings of Terror&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"cosmetic\"&gt;cosmetic&lt;/a&gt;.\nThere is no restriction on the rate of unlocks other than the materials the player can gather. A &lt;a href=\"Challenge%20Rift\"&gt;Challenge Rift&lt;/a&gt; cache is the only time-restricted material, although some others may be hard to come by.\nAfter unlocking any Seal's powers, its generic text changes to a small story scrap about &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;Sanctuary&lt;/a&gt;'s tumultuous past, and the Seal's name is revealed.\nCosts.\nBelow are the costs to unlock additional Seals:\n\u2020 Bounty materials: &lt;a href=\"Khanduran%20Rune\"&gt;Khanduran Rune&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Caldeum%20Nightshade\"&gt;Caldeum Nightshade&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Arreat%20War%20Tapestry\"&gt;Arreat War Tapestry&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Corrupted%20Angel%20Flesh\"&gt;Corrupted Angel Flesh&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Westmarch%20Holy%20Water\"&gt;Westmarch Holy Water&lt;/a&gt;"}
{"id": "26324", "revid": "1773829", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=26324", "title": "Altar of Sadness", "text": "Altar of Sadness is an &lt;a href=\"event%20%28Diablo%20III%29\"&gt;event&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Act%20V%20%28Diablo%20III%29\"&gt;Act V&lt;/a&gt; of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". It takes place in &lt;a href=\"Briarthorn%20Cemetery\"&gt;Briarthorn Cemetery&lt;/a&gt;, in a partially fenced section of the graveyard containing a conspicuous altar in the middle.\nTouching the altar causes a number of &lt;a href=\"Swift%20Flesheater\"&gt;Swift Flesheater&lt;/a&gt;s to emerge from the ground, followed shortly by the &lt;a href=\"Unique%20Monsters\"&gt;unique&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Risen%20Bones\"&gt;Risen Bones&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Funerus\"&gt;Funerus&lt;/a&gt;. They must all be killed.\nObjectives.\nUsing the Altar completes the event, dropping approximately a &lt;a href=\"Radiant%20Chest\"&gt;Radiant Chest&lt;/a&gt; worth of loot and awarding gold and experience."}
{"id": "8339", "revid": "845641", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=8339", "title": "Altar of the Heavens", "text": "The Altar of the Heavens is the pedestal found in the &lt;a href=\"Arreat%20Summit\"&gt;Arreat Summit&lt;/a&gt;. \nThe player must activate this holy altar to interact with the &lt;a href=\"Ancients\"&gt;Ancients&lt;/a&gt;. The top glows red after clicking on the altar, and after the speech given by &lt;a href=\"Talic\"&gt;Talic&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Madawc\"&gt;Madawc&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Korlic\"&gt;Korlic&lt;/a&gt;, the Ancients come alive and must be defeated in order for the spiked gate to the &lt;a href=\"Worldstone%20Keep\"&gt;Worldstone Keep&lt;/a&gt; to open.\nAfter the Ancients have been defeated, the Altar no longer responds to being clicked. \nUpon activating the Altar.\n\"We are the spirits of the &lt;a href=\"Nephalem\"&gt;Nephalem&lt;/a&gt;, the Ancient Ones. We have been chosen to guard sacred &lt;a href=\"Mount%20Arreat\"&gt;Mount Arreat&lt;/a&gt;,\" \n\"wherein the &lt;a href=\"Worldstone\"&gt;Worldstone&lt;/a&gt; rests. Few are worthy to stand in its presence. Fewer still can comprehend its true\" \"purpose. Before you enter, you must defeat us.\" "}
{"id": "47747", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=47747", "title": "Altars of Illumination", "text": "Altars of Illumination are &lt;a href=\"Cathedral%20of%20Light\"&gt;Cathedral of Light&lt;/a&gt; structures found throughout the &lt;a href=\"Fractured%20Peaks\"&gt;Fractured Peaks&lt;/a&gt;.\nLore.\nThe Altars sit on ancient sites in the Peaks that were once used by a different faith (likely &lt;a href=\"Skatsim\"&gt;Skatsim&lt;/a&gt;). The ruins were torn down and the stone repurposed to construct the Altars. This was done deliberately, to erased and replace the vestiges of what the Church considered to be superstitious and heretical practices.\n&lt;a href=\"Lorath%20Nahr\"&gt;Lorath Nahr&lt;/a&gt; speculated that one day, the Altars would be torn down by some new, ascendant faith. Such is the nature of &lt;a href=\"human\"&gt;human&lt;/a&gt; history.\nIn-game.\nThe Altars can be found across the Fractured Peaks zone in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20IV\"&gt;Diablo IV&lt;/a&gt;\", mostly as dodads."}
